Detailed Crash Investigation Supplement
(For review by the MSP Crash Team)




Section I. - Narrative
On June 1, 2023, Sgt. Jake Sullivan of the Cumberland City Police Department (CPD) Crash Team requested my assistance with the imaging of an airbag control module (ACM) of a 2015 Chevrolet Equinox.  Sgt. Sullivan advised that the Equinox had been involved in an attempted murder in the area of Milton Place in Cumberland, MD.  He also stated that the Equinox was possibly used as a weapon against a pedestrian who had just been in an argument with the driver of the Equinox.  The vehicle struck the lower leg of the pedestrian as it also struck a barrier pole near a gas meter.  The pedestrian then drew a pistol and fired a single round through the windshield striking the driver.  Both the pedestrian and Equinox fled the scene and were later located.  Sgt. Sullivan was specifically interested in the acceleration of the Equinox prior to striking the pedestrian.  Sgt. Sullivan authored a search warrant for the data from the ACM of the Equinox.

On June 2, 2023, I met Sgt. Sullivan at CPD to execute the search warrant.  I began by confirming that the VIN on the search warrant matched the VIN on the Equinox.  The damage was contained to the left front corner of the vehicle with a bullet hole in the lower left corner of the windshield (all damage described as if sitting in the driver's seat).  48 digital photographs were taken of the vehicle and the imaging.  The tires on the vehicle, were the size recommended for the Equinox.  The Bosch Crash Data Retrieval (CDR) tool was connected to the diagnostic link connector of the Equinox.  The tool was connected to a laptop equipped with CDR software version 23.1.1.  The tool imaged the ACM and the data was saved.

Two non-deployment events were recovered from the ACM.  Non-deployment events record data but do not deploy the airbags.  A review of the data limitations did not reveal anything that would invalidate the data.  The ignition cycle when the ACM was imaged was 24,131.

Event Record 1:
The complete file was recorded for this event.  This event was the first event of a multi-event.  The ignition cycle for the event was 24,129, which was two ignition cycles before when the ACM was imaged.  This difference of two can be accounted for by the vehicle being towed and verify that the data is from the attempted murder.  The data confirmed that no airbags had deployed and also showed that neither front seat belt was buckled.  Five seconds of Pre-crash data were saved in half second increments (see chart below).


For this event the accelerator pedal went from 0 to 41% then 23%, 18% then back to 0 with the brake applied.

Event Record 2:
The complete file was recorded for this event.  This was the second event of the multi-event, and it occurred .87 seconds after Event Record 1.  It is expected that an event occurred that did not record between these two events.  This is due to the .87 seconds between events not lining up with the data from the events.  Due to the differences in data from event 1 to event 2, it is believed that event 1 actually occurred at least 5 seconds before event record 2.  Event Record 2 also occurred at an ignition cycle of 24,129, linking the data to this incident.  Five seconds of pre-crash data was again saved in half second increments (see below chart).

For this event the accelerator pedal position changed for each sample.  The position ranged from no input up to 99%.  The brakes were applied for the two samples when no accelerator input occurred.  The engine rpm's were high during most of the recording.  The vehicle speed fluctuated during the event, as low as 11 mph and as high as 22 mph at -.5 seconds.

 
Section II. - Attachments that were included in for this report:

The following items were attached to this report: 
CPD Search Warrant
CDR Report


48 Digital photographs were uploaded to Veripic
 
Conclusion:
Based on the CDR data, it is believed that Event Record 1 occurred more than five seconds before Event Record 2.  It is also believed that an event occurred between the two events, but it was not recorded other than saying that event record 2 occurred .87 seconds after it.  Event Record 2 showed that the Equinox was not being driven in a normal fashion.  It is extremely rare to see such high accelerator pedal positions.  With brake applications in the middle of the extremely high accelerator pedal positions, especially in an urban environment, it is believed that this shows that the driver of the Equinox was intentionally chasing down and attempting to strike the pedestrian with the vehicle.

This report and all attachments will be forwarded to the CPD and C3I.

This case is closed for the Crash Team.
